body_raw:
In my book on fluid mechanics there is an expression $$  oldsymbol{
abla}\cdot  oldsymbol{	au}_{ij} $$ where $ oldsymbol{	au}_{ij}$ is a rank-2 tensor (=matrix). Given that $ oldsymbol
abla=(\partial_x, \partial_y, \partial_z)$, a vector, what do I get when I dot it with a matrix? If I was to write $ oldsymbol{
abla}\cdot  oldsymbol{	au}_{ij}$ in Einstein notation, then how would it look? The tensor $ oldsymbol{	au}_{ij}$ is given by $$   egin{pmatrix}   	au_{xx} & 	au_{yx} & 	au_{zx} \   	au_{xy} & 	au_{yy} & 	au_{zy} \   	au_{xz} & 	au_{yz} & 	au_{zz}  \end{pmatrix} $$ and the dot-product yields (by comparison with later expressions in the chapter) $$  oldsymbol{
abla}\cdot  oldsymbol{	au}_{ij} = \mathbf{i}(\partial_x 	au_{xx} + \partial_y 	au_{yx} + \partial_z 	au_{zx})+\mathbf{j}(\partial_x 	au_{xy} + \partial_y 	au_{yy} + \partial_z 	au_{zy}) + \mathbf{k}(\partial_x 	au_{xz} + \partial_y 	au_{yz} + \partial_z 	au_{zz}) $$ However, I don't see how this last expression comes about.

